# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1976-summer-olympics
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1976-summer-olympics/1600s-timeline-of-montreal-history-p01] The **timeline of Montreal history** is a chronology of significant events in the history of Montreal, Canada's second-most populated city, with about 3.5 million residents in 2018, and the fourth-largest French-speaking city in the world.
[src:1976-summer-olympics/1732-montreal-earthquake] The **1732 Montreal earthquake** was a 5.8 mbLg magnitude earthquake that struck New France at 11:00 a.m. on September 16, 1732.
[src:1976-summer-olympics/1732-montreal-earthquake] This was one of the major earthquakes that occurred in the Western Quebec seismic zone.
[src:1976-summer-olympics/1976-summer-olympics] Montreal was awarded the rights to the 1976 Games at the 69th IOC Session in Amsterdam on May 12, 1970, over the bids of Moscow and Los Angeles.
[src:1976-summer-olympics/1976-summer-olympics] It is the only Summer Olympic Games to be held in Canada.
[src:1976-summer-olympics/1976-summer-olympics] Toronto hosted the 1976 Summer Paralympics the same year as the Montreal Olympics, also the only Summer Paralympics to be held in Canada.
[src:1976-summer-olympics/1976-summer-olympics] Calgary and Vancouver later hosted the Winter Olympic Games in 1988 and 2010, respectively.
[src:1976-summer-olympics/1976-summer-olympics] This was the first of two consecutive Olympic games held in North America, followed by the 1980 Winter Olympics in Lake Placid.
[src:1976-summer-olympics/1976-summer-olympics] The Soviet Union won the most gold and overall medals, with the Eastern Bloc having seven countries in the top 10 of the medal table.
[src:1976-summer-olympics/1976-summer-olympics] The vote occurred at the 69th IOC Session in Amsterdam, Netherlands on May 12, 1970.
[src:1976-summer-olympics/1976-summer-olympics] While Los Angeles and Moscow were viewed as the favourites, given that they represented the world's two main powers, many of the smaller and neutral countries supported Montreal as an underdog and as a relatively neutral site for the Games.
[src:1976-summer-olympics/1976-summer-olympics] Los Angeles was eliminated after the first round, and Montreal won over Moscow in the second round.
[src:1976-summer-olympics/1976-summer-olympics] Moscow and Los Angeles would go on to host the next two Summer Games, 1980 and 1984 Summer Olympics, respectively, which were also marked by political boycotts (for instance, the U.S.-led boycott of the Soviet invasion of Afghanistan in 1979).
[src:1976-summer-olympics/1976-summer-olympics] One blank vote was cast in the second and final round.
[src:1976-summer-olympics/1976-summer-olympics] The Soviet state media accused the IOC of political corruption following the vote, accusing them of facilitating the Soviet Union's loss.
[src:1976-summer-olympics/1976-summer-olympics] Toronto had made its third attempt for the Olympics, as did Hamilton.
[src:1976-summer-olympics/1976-summer-olympics] Still, they failed to win the support of the Canadian Olympic Committee, which selected Montreal instead.
[src:1976-summer-olympics/1976-summer-olympics] Another candidate was the Italian city of Florence, which announced that it would withdraw from contention two months before the vote.
[src:1976-summer-olympics/1976-summer-olympics] Robert Bourassa, then the Premier of Quebec, asked Prime Minister Pierre Trudeau to advise Canada's monarch Elizabeth II to attend the opening of the games.
[src:1976-summer-olympics/1976-summer-olympics] However, Bourassa later became unsettled about how unpopular the move might be with sovereigntists in the province, annoying Trudeau, who had already made arrangements.
[src:1976-summer-olympics/1976-summer-olympics] René Lévesque, the leader of the Parti Québécois at the time, sent his own letter to Buckingham Palace, asking the Queen to refuse her prime minister's request, but she did not oblige Lévesque as he was out of his jurisdiction in offering advice to the Sovereign.
[src:1976-summer-olympics/1976-summer-olympics] In 1976, Trudeau, succumbing to pressure from the People's Republic of China, issued an order barring Taiwan from participating as China in the 1976 Montreal Olympics, although it was technically a matter for the IOC.
[src:1976-summer-olympics/1976-summer-olympics] His action strained relations with the United States – from President Ford to future President Carter and the press.
[src:1976-summer-olympics/1976-summer-olympics] Trudeau's action was widely condemned as having brought shame on Canada by succumbing to political pressure to keep the Taiwanese delegation from competing under its name.
[src:1976-summer-olympics/1976-summer-olympics] The mascot was a beaver named Amik, whose name was chosen after a national competition.
[src:1976-summer-olympics/1976-summer-olympics] The *Oxford Olympics Study* estimates the outturn cost of the Montreal 1976 Summer Olympics at US$6.1 billion in 2015 dollars and cost overrun at 720% in real terms.
[src:1976-summer-olympics/1976-summer-olympics] *Indirect* capital costs are not included, such as those for road, rail, or airport infrastructure, or for hotel upgrades or other business investment incurred in preparation for the Games but not directly related to staging the Games.
[src:1976-summer-olympics/1976-summer-olympics] The cost overrun for Montreal 1976 is the highest cost overrun on record for any Olympics.
[src:1976-summer-olympics/1976-summer-olympics] The cost and cost overrun for Montreal 1976 compares with costs of US$4.6 billion and a cost overrun of 51% for Rio de Janeiro in 2016 and $15 billion and 76% for London in 2012.
[src:1976-summer-olympics/1976-summer-olympics] The average cost for the Summer Games from 1960 to 2016 was $5.2 billion in 2015 dollars, and the average cost overrun was 176%.
[src:1976-summer-olympics/1976-summer-olympics] French architect Roger Taillibert, who designed the Olympic stadium, recounted in his 2000 book *Notre Cher Stade Olympique* that he and Mayor Drapeau tried hard to buy off Desjardins, even taking him to a lunch at the exclusive Ritz-Carlton hotel in a vain attempt to end the "delays".
[src:1976-summer-olympics/1976-summer-olympics] He suggests that Quebec Premier Robert Bourassa ultimately made a secret deal to buy off Desjardins, which allowed work to proceed.
[src:1976-summer-olympics/1976-summer-olympics] Taillibert wrote in *Notre Cher Stade Olympique* "If the Olympic Games took place, it was thanks to Dede Desjardins.
[src:1976-summer-olympics/1976-summer-olympics] What irony!" The delays and scandals caused Quebec premier Robert Bourassa to take over the preparations of the games in November 1975.
[src:1976-summer-olympics/1976-summer-olympics] The Vélodrome de Montréal, which was scheduled for opening in 1974, was finally completed in June 1976, a month before the opening ceremony.
[src:1976-summer-olympics/1976-summer-olympics] The opening ceremony of the 1976 Summer Olympic Games was held at the incomplete Olympic Stadium in Montreal, Quebec on Saturday afternoon, July 17, 1976, in front of an audience of some 73,000 in the stadium and an estimated half billion watching on television.
[src:1976-summer-olympics/1976-summer-olympics] Following an air show by the Canadian Forces Air Command's Snowbirds aerobatic flight demonstration squadron in the sunny skies above the stadium, the ceremony officially began at 3:00 pm with a trumpet fanfare and the arrival of Elizabeth II, as Queen of Canada.
[src:1976-summer-olympics/1976-summer-olympics] The Queen entered the Royal Box with her consort, Prince Philip, Duke of Edinburgh, and her son, Prince Andrew.
[src:1976-summer-olympics/1976-summer-olympics] (Her daughter, Princess Anne, was competing as a member of Great Britain's equestrian team.
[src:1976-summer-olympics/1976-summer-olympics] The parade of athletes began moments later with the arrival of the Greek team, and concluded with the entrance of the Canadian team.
[src:1976-summer-olympics/1976-summer-olympics] All other teams entered the stadium according to French alphabetical order (as the host city's main language).
[src:1976-summer-olympics/1976-summer-olympics] The ceremony was marked by the adorning of Israel's flag with a black mourning ribbon, in memory of the eleven athletes and coaches killed by Palestinian terrorists at the previous Summer Olympic Games in Munich four years earlier.
[src:1976-summer-olympics/1976-summer-olympics] Although most would eventually boycott the Games in the days to follow, a number of African delegations did march in the parade.
[src:1976-summer-olympics/1976-summer-olympics] Much of the music performed for the parade was arranged by Victor Vogel and was inspired by late Quebecois composer André Mathieu.
[src:1976-summer-olympics/1976-summer-olympics] Immediately following the parade, a troupe of 80 female dancers dressed in white (representing the 80th anniversary of the revival of the Olympic Games) performed a brief dance in the outline of the Olympic rings.
[src:1976-summer-olympics/1976-summer-olympics] Following that came the official speeches, first by Roger Rousseau, head of the Montreal Olympic organizing committee, and Lord Killanin.
[src:1976-summer-olympics/1976-summer-olympics] Her Majesty was then invited to proclaim the Games open, which she did, first in French, then in English.
[src:1976-summer-olympics/1976-summer-olympics] Accompanied by the Olympic Hymn, the Olympic flag was carried into the stadium and hoisted at the west end of the stadium.
[src:1976-summer-olympics/1976-summer-olympics] The flag was carried by eight men and hoisted by four women, representing the ten provinces and two territories (at the time) of Canada.
[src:1976-summer-olympics/1976-summer-olympics] As the flag was hoisted, an all-male choir performed an a cappella version of the Olympic Hymn.
[src:1976-summer-olympics/1976-summer-olympics] Once the flag was hosted, a troupe of Bavarian dancers representing Munich, host of the previous Summer Olympics, entered the stadium with the Antwerp flag.
[src:1976-summer-olympics/1976-summer-olympics] Following a brief dance, that flag was then passed from the Mayor of Munich to the IOC President and then to the Mayor of Montreal.
[src:1976-summer-olympics/1976-summer-olympics] Next came a presentation of traditional Québécois folk dancers.
[src:1976-summer-olympics/1976-summer-olympics] The two troupes merged in dance together to the strains of "Vive le Compagnie" and exited the stadium with the Antwerp Flag, which would be displayed at Montreal City Hall until the opening of the 1980 Summer Olympics in Moscow.
[src:1976-summer-olympics/1976-summer-olympics] Three cannons were then fired, as the 80-member troupe of female dancers unfolded special crates that released doves and ribbons in the five Olympic colours.
[src:1976-summer-olympics/1976-summer-olympics] Another trumpet fanfare announced the arrival of the Olympic Flame.
[src:1976-summer-olympics/1976-summer-olympics] The torch was carried by 15-year-olds Stéphane Préfontaine and Sandra Henderson, chosen as representatives of the unity within Canada's linguistic heritage.
[src:1976-summer-olympics/1976-summer-olympics] This would also be the first time two people would light the Olympic flame.
[src:1976-summer-olympics/1976-summer-olympics] The duo would make a lap of the stadium and then climbed a staircase on a special dais at the centre of the stadium to set the Olympic flame alight in a temporary white aluminum cauldron.
[src:1976-summer-olympics/1976-summer-olympics] The flame was later transported to a more permanent cauldron just outside the running track to burn throughout the duration of the Games.
[src:1976-summer-olympics/1976-summer-olympics] A choir then performed the Olympic Cantata as onlookers admired the Olympic flame.
[src:1976-summer-olympics/1976-summer-olympics] The "Youth of Canada" took to the track to perform a colourful choreographed segment with flags, ribbons and a variety of rhythmic gymnast performers.
[src:1976-summer-olympics/1976-summer-olympics] The flag bearers of each team then circled around the speaker's dais as Pierre St-Jean recited the Athletes' Oath and Maurice Forget recited the Judges' Oath, in English and in French, with right hands over their hearts and Canadian flags clutched in their left.
[src:1976-summer-olympics/1976-summer-olympics] Finally, a choral performance of "O Canada" in both French and English marked the close of the opening ceremony, as the announcers concluded with a declaration of the Games motto: 'Vive les Jeux de Montreal!
[src:1976-summer-olympics/1976-summer-olympics] The Montreal ceremony would be the last of its kind in Summer Games, as future Olympic ceremonies, beginning with the new Olympic Charter were reinforced before the 1980 Summer Olympics, would become more focused on the host country's culture.
[src:1976-summer-olympics/1976-summer-olympics] Because of the Munich massacre, security at these games was visible.
[src:1976-summer-olympics/1976-summer-olympics] The extensive security measures included the requirement for all workers to hold a valid accreditation.
[src:1976-summer-olympics/1976-summer-olympics] Surveillance of acoustics was installed in the Olympic Village where athletes were accommodated.
[src:1976-summer-olympics/1976-summer-olympics] Furthermore, a systematic installation of closed-circuit television (CCTV) was attempted for the first time in the history of the Olympic games.
[src:1976-summer-olympics/1976-summer-olympics] There was a desire by the IOC's program commission to reduce the number of competitors and a number of recommendations were put to the IOC's executive board on February 23, 1973, which were all accepted.
[src:1976-summer-olympics/1976-summer-olympics] Rowing was the only sport where the number of competitors was increased, and women were admitted for the first time in Olympic history.
[src:1976-summer-olympics/1976-summer-olympics] Four nations made their first Summer Olympic appearance in Montreal: Andorra (which had its overall Olympic debut a few months before in Innsbruck Winter Olympics), Antigua and Barbuda (as *Antigua*), Cayman Islands, and Papua New Guinea.
[src:1976-summer-olympics/1976-summer-olympics] Numbers in parentheses indicate the number of athletes from each nation that competed at the Games.
[src:1976-summer-olympics/1976-summer-olympics] These are the top ten nations that won medals at the 1976 Games.
[src:1976-summer-olympics/1976-summer-olympics] Canada placed 27th with only 11 medals in total, none of them being gold.
[src:1976-summer-olympics/1976-summer-olympics] Canada remains the only host nation of a Summer Olympics to fail to win at least one gold medal.
[src:1976-summer-olympics/1976-summer-olympics] It also did not win any gold medals at the 1988 Winter Olympics in Calgary.
[src:1976-summer-olympics/1976-summer-olympics] However, Canada went on to win the most gold medals at the 2010 Winter Olympics in Vancouver.
[src:1976-summer-olympics/1976-summer-olympics] The Games were dominated by the Soviet Bloc, with the USSR and its satellites occupying seven out of top ten places in the medal standings.
[src:1976-summer-olympics/1976-summer-olympics] Twenty-nine countries boycotted the Games due to the refusal of the IOC to ban New Zealand, after the New Zealand national rugby union team had toured South Africa earlier in 1976.
[src:1976-summer-olympics/1976-summer-olympics] The boycott was led by Congolese official Jean-Claude Ganga.
[src:1976-summer-olympics/1976-summer-olympics] Some of the boycotting nations (including Morocco, Cameroon and Egypt) had already participated, however, and withdrew after the first few days.
[src:1976-summer-olympics/1976-summer-olympics] Senegal and Ivory Coast were the only African countries that competed throughout the duration of the Games.
[src:1976-summer-olympics/1976-summer-olympics] Elsewhere, Afghanistan, Albania, Burma, Iraq, Guyana, Sri Lanka and Syria also opted to join the Congolese-led boycott.
[src:1976-summer-olympics/1976-summer-olympics] South Africa had been banned from the Olympics since 1964 due to its apartheid policies.
[src:1976-summer-olympics/1976-summer-olympics] Other countries, such as El Salvador and Zaire, did not participate in Montreal for purely economic reasons.
[src:1976-summer-olympics/1976-summer-olympics] An unrelated boycott of the Montreal Games was the main issue between the Republic of China (ROC) and the People's Republic of China (PRC).
[src:1976-summer-olympics/1976-summer-olympics] The ROC team withdrew from the games when Canada's Liberal government under Pierre Trudeau told it that the name "Republic of China" was not permissible at the Games because Canada had officially recognized the PRC in 1970.
[src:1976-summer-olympics/1976-summer-olympics] Canada attempted a compromise by allowing the ROC the continued use of its national flag and anthem in the Montreal Olympic activities; the ROC refused.
[src:1976-summer-olympics/1976-summer-olympics] In 1979 the IOC established in the Nagoya Resolution that the PRC agreed to participate in IOC activities if the Republic of China was referred to as "Chinese Taipei".
[src:1976-summer-olympics/1976-summer-olympics] Another boycott would occur before the ROC would accept the provisions of the 1979 resolution.
[src:1976-summer-olympics/1976-summer-olympics] Researchers from Germany in 2013 reported that West Germany had a state-sponsored doping program, and speculated it was in response to doping in East Germany which had existed for decades.
[src:1976-summer-olympics/1976-summer-olympics] ABC Sports paid US$25-million for television broadcast rights in the United States, and produced 76.5 hours of coverage.
[src:1976-summer-olympics/1976-summer-olympics] CBC Sports budgeted less than CAD$2-million and produced 169 hours of coverage, compared to 14 hours of programming at the 1972 Summer Olympics.
[src:1976-summer-olympics/1976-summer-olympics] The network expanded its coverage in 1976, when convinced there would be increased media interest from Canadians.
[src:1976-summer-olympics/1976-summer-olympics] When the network was criticized for spending taxpayer dollars, executive producer Bob Moir toured the country to explain the project and boasted that, "the biggest team in Montreal will be the CBC team...
[src:1976-summer-olympics/1976-summer-olympics] It will be bigger than the Canadian Olympic team".
[src:1976-summer-olympics/1976-summer-olympics] CBC Sports had 245 people on its crew, and aired from 9 am until 11 pm daily, taking breaks only for newscasts.
[src:1976-summer-olympics/1976-summer-olympics] Ted Reynolds and Lloyd Robertson co-hosted coverage of the opening ceremonies.
[src:1976-summer-olympics/1976-summer-olympics] In 1976, CBC Sports began its practice of talking live with athletes immediately after events, and built a studio for the interviews.
[src:1976-summer-olympics/1976-summer-olympics] CBC broadcasters were given information kits on the athletes, prepared by Jack Sullivan, the former sports editor of The Canadian Press.
[src:1976-summer-olympics/1976-summer-olympics] The legacy of the Montreal Olympics is complex.
[src:1976-summer-olympics/1976-summer-olympics] Many citizens regard the Olympiad as a financial disaster for the city as it faced debts for 30 years after the Games had finished.
[src:1976-summer-olympics/1976-summer-olympics] The retractable roof of the Olympic Stadium never properly worked and on several occasions has torn, prompting the stadium to be closed for extended periods of time for repairs.
[src:1976-summer-olympics/1976-summer-olympics] The failure of the Montreal Expos baseball club is largely blamed on the failure of the Olympic Stadium to transition into an effective and popular venue for the club – given the massive capacity of the stadium, it often looked unimpressive even with regular crowds in excess of 20,000 spectators.
[src:1976-summer-olympics/1976-summer-olympics] The Quebec provincial government took over construction when it became evident in 1975 that work had fallen far behind schedule.
[src:1976-summer-olympics/1976-summer-olympics] Work was still ongoing just weeks before the opening date, and the tower was not built.
[src:1976-summer-olympics/1976-summer-olympics] Mayor Jean Drapeau had confidently predicted in 1970 that "the Olympics can no more have a deficit than a man can have a baby", but the debt racked up to a billion dollars that the Quebec government mandated the city pay in full.
[src:1976-summer-olympics/1976-summer-olympics] This would prompt cartoonist Aislin to draw a pregnant Drapeau on the telephone saying, "Allo, Morgentaler?" in reference to a Montreal abortion provider.
[src:1976-summer-olympics/1976-summer-olympics] The Olympic Stadium was designed by French architect Roger Taillibert.
[src:1976-summer-olympics/1976-summer-olympics] It is often nicknamed "The Big O" as a reference to both its name and to the doughnut-shape of the permanent component of the stadium's roof, though "The Big Owe" has been used to reference the astronomical cost of the stadium and the 1976 Olympics as a whole.
[src:1976-summer-olympics/1976-summer-olympics] It has never had an effective retractable roof, and the tower (called the Montreal Tower) was completed only eleven years after the Olympic Games, in 1987.
[src:1976-summer-olympics/1976-summer-olympics] In December 2006 the stadium's costs were finally paid in full.
[src:1976-summer-olympics/1976-summer-olympics] The total expenditure (including repairs, renovations, construction, interest, and inflation) amounted to C$1.61 billion.
[src:1976-summer-olympics/1976-summer-olympics] Today the stadium lacks a permanent tenant, as the Montreal Alouettes and Montreal Expos have moved, though it does host some individual games of the Alouettes as well as CF Montréal (formerly the Montreal Impact).
[src:1976-summer-olympics/1976-summer-olympics] One of the streets surrounding the Olympic Stadium was renamed to honour Pierre de Coubertin, the founder of the Olympics.
[src:1976-summer-olympics/1976-summer-olympics] The boycott by African nations over the inclusion of New Zealand, whose rugby team had played in South Africa that year, was a contributing factor in the massive protests and civil disobedience that occurred during the 1981 Springbok Tour of New Zealand.
[src:1976-summer-olympics/1976-summer-olympics] Official sporting contacts between South Africa and New Zealand did not occur again until after the fall of apartheid.
[src:1976-summer-olympics/1976-summer-olympics] Australia's failure to win a gold medal led the country to create the Australian Institute of Sport.
[src:1976-summer-olympics/1976-summer-olympics] In 2016, the 40th anniversary celebrations were held.
[src:1976-summer-olympics/1976-summer-olympics] In conjunction with the celebrations, the 2016 Quebec Games were held.
[src:1976-summer-olympics/1976-summer-olympics] The games were the subject of *Games of the XXI Olympiad (Jeux de la XXIe olympiade)*, a 1977 documentary film by Jean Beaudin, Marcel Carrière, Georges Dufaux and Jean-Claude Labrecque.
[src:1976-summer-olympics/1976-summer-olympics] The 1976 games were also an inspiration for Australian band Black Cab's double album of 2014 entitled *Games of the XXI Olympiad*.
